rator to a particle accelerator &quot;afterburner&quot;. The design would be massive for sure, such a particle accelerator would not be light. I am not sure how much extra thrust accelerating the particles that much would cause. Unless the engine has a high specific power (jet power/mass of propellant), which I don't think this would, specific inpulses (exaust velocity/gravitational constant) beyong 50000-100000s will be counterproductive. Without increasing specific power, increasing specific inpulse to high levels produces a low thrust engine like an ion drive. External pulse thrusters, fission and fusion, get around this by having both high specific power and high exaust velocities. By not containing the plasma the exaust can operate at higher temperatures, thus high velocities, and the energy of the plasma wave and dense propellant gives them high thrust.<br>
<br>
Ion engines offer simplicity compaired to a complex design like VASMIR, but not as much promise. I personaly like the idea behind VASMIR, but it still can't avoid having to spiral out of orbit like other electric rockets- the high thrust mode is still not that high thrust. The thrust modulation decreases interplanetary trip time, but with the extra time tacked on the advantage isn't as great over NTR's. The efficiency advantage is still a great reason to develope it. <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=whitestar60>whitestar60</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/14/02 7:40:30 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=186.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.b5tech.net/art/b5/vorlonangry.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What are the types of next generation propulsion?</span><hr size=1> I also agree that under dire situations,Ie incoming asteriod, ect. <br>
